4 A JOINT RESOLUTION OF THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE STATE OF
5 MONTANA REQUESTING AN INTERIM STUDY ON THE PROPERTY INSURANCE MARKET IN MONTANA;
6 AND REQUIRING THAT THE FINAL RESULTS OF THE STUDY BE REPORTED TO THE 70TH
7 LEGISLATURE.
8
9 WHEREAS, the increasing costs of insurance are further exacerbating major housing affordability
10 challenges in Montana for homeowners, landlords, and tenants; and
11 WHEREAS, high property insurance premiums hurt Montana businesses; and
12 WHEREAS, property insurance rates have been increasing significantly for all Montanans, regardless
13 of where they live; and
14 WHEREAS, Montana had the fifth-fastest increase in rates in the nation in 2024, and Montana’s
15 cumulative increases in insurance rates from 2019 to 2024 were 44.3%; and
16 WHEREAS, from 2012 to 2022, the percentage increase in Montana’s insurance premiums, as tracked
17 by the National Association of Insurance Commissioners, has outpaced a national increase in rates, increasing
18 twice as fast as the national average in 5 of those 10 years; and
19 WHEREAS, the coverage provided by insurers is simultaneously shrinking for homeowners and
20 businesses despite the rapidly rising rates of property insurance; and
21 WHEREAS, Montana home values are rising unrelentingly, with the Montana Department of Revenue
22 reporting that the median residential property value increased by 32% in 2023 alone and with the Montana
23 Department of Labor reporting increases in home values of 5% to 25% each year compared to the preceding
24 decade from 2012 to 2022; and
25 WHEREAS, the rising cost of insurance may lead to difficulties in obtaining mortgages as financial
26 institutions become increasingly hesitant to approve loans in regions facing high insurance risks; and
27 WHEREAS, Montana has the second-highest risk in the nation for catastrophic wildfire impacts on
28 property, and some insurers are withdrawing from high-risk areas, leaving homeowners to take on more risk or
