1 face higher premiums; and
2 WHEREAS, 7% of U.S. homeowners lack insurance, with higher rates in Montana than in many other
3 states; and
4 WHEREAS, Montana’s Indian and other minority populations, face disproportionately high risks from
5 wildfires and may struggle to afford rising insurance premiums or recover from losses; and
6 WHEREAS, Montana experienced 2,388 wildfires in 2024, which burned 387,966 acres, and of the
7 11.7 million recorded acres burned in the past 138 years, 70% have burned since 2000 and roughly half of the
8 acres burned prior to 2000 were in a single year, 1910, which demonstrates the increasing frequency and
9 financial burden of wildfires in the state; and
10 WHEREAS, the number of homes in high wildfire risk areas in Montana has doubled since 1990, with
11 development continuing at a rate of 450 homes a year, increasing the risk and cost of fire suppression; and
12 WHEREAS, the National Association of Insurance Commissioners reports that insurers have
13 experienced losses in 4 of the past 5 years, with insurers in Montana reporting losses in 3 of the past 5 years,
14 leading to higher premiums and reduced coverage; and
15 WHEREAS, according to the U.S. International Trade Commission, reinsurance costs had increased by
16 as much as 50% at the January 2024 renewals, and it is challenging for some carriers to even find reinsurance.
17
18 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF
19 THE STATE OF MONTANA:
20 That the Legislative Council be requested to designate an appropriate interim committee, pursuant to
21 section 5-5-217, MCA, to:
22 (1) evaluate the causes of Montana’s increasing property insurance;
23 (2) determine the impact of these causes on rates; and
24 (3) analyze policy strategies that could stabilize the property insurance market and develop
25 property insurance approaches for more accessible and affordable property insurance in the state.
26 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that all aspects of the study, including presentation and review
27 requirements, be concluded prior to September 15, 2026.
28 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that the final results of the study, including any findings, conclusions,
